# BadaBhai repo toolchain pin — the Flutter SDK the two mobile apps are built and
# CI-gated on. TD71 (#462).
#
# WHY THIS FILE EXISTS
# Dev machines ran Flutter 3.27.4 while CI ran 3.35.7, and nothing in the repo
# stated which was correct. That gap produced TD71 twice: worker-app's
# pubspec.lock was committed from 3.27.4 (carrying a `_macros` entry that does
# not exist in Dart 3.7+), so CI's `pub get` silently re-resolved and rewrote it
# and the green "Worker app (analyze/test)" check was validating a resolution
# that was never committed. TD61 was the same class of drift, inverted. The pin
# now lives in ONE place devs and tooling can both read.
#
# HOW IT IS ENFORCED (three places — keep them in lockstep on any bump)
#   1. this file                                     — dev machines
#   2. .github/workflows/worker-app.yml  (flutter-version: "3.35.7")
#   3. .github/workflows/payer-app.yml   (flutter-version: "3.35.7")
# The apps' `environment:` blocks (apps/{worker,payer}-app/pubspec.yaml) floor at
# Flutter >=3.35.0 so an old SDK fails LOUD at `pub get` rather than as a
# confusing transitive resolution error.
#
# WHY .tool-versions AND NOT .fvmrc
# This format is read by asdf and mise, and IGNORED — harmlessly, with no error
# and no install prompt — by anyone using neither. It does not intercept a plain
# `flutter` command, so nobody is forced to adopt a version manager; for them it
# is simply the documented answer to "which SDK?". fvm was the alternative but is
# more intrusive (it wants `fvm flutter ...` at every call site and an .fvm/
# symlink dir), and `.fvmrc` is resolved from the current directory rather than
# by walking up the tree, so it could not sit at the repo root and cover both
# apps. asdf/mise DO walk up, so this one file applies inside apps/worker-app
# and apps/payer-app. It is also the format `subosito/flutter-action@v2` can
# consume via its `flutter-version-file:` input — so the workflows can later be
# pointed here and the drift closed structurally instead of by convention.
#
# The `-stable` suffix is the asdf-flutter version identifier for the same build
# CI names plainly as "3.35.7" (Dart 3.9.2).
flutter 3.35.7-stable

# Node is deliberately NOT pinned here: package.json already declares
# `engines.node: ">=20"` + `packageManager: pnpm@11.5.2`, and hard-pinning one
# exact Node version in this file would be STRICTER than the contract the repo
# actually holds itself to — it would break asdf users who are on a perfectly
# valid Node 22.
